<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.D2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="division" searchtype="LEGISLATION DIVISION" subdoc="false" toc-caption="DIVISION 2 CONTEMPT IN THE FACE OR HEARING OF THE COURT [rr 2&#x2013;4]">
<leg:heading><desig searchtype="DIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.D2" type="ext"/>DIVISION 2</designum></desig><title searchtype="DIV-TITLE">CONTEMPT IN THE FACE OR HEARING OF THE COURT [rr 2&#x2013;4]</title></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 55 r 2] r 2 Arrest">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 55 r 2]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Arrest</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>2</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Where it is alleged, or appears to the Court on its own view, that a person is guilty of contempt of court, committed in the face of the Court or in the hearing of the Court, the Court may:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2..A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2..A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>by oral order direct that the contemnor be brought before the Court; or</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2..B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R2..B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>issue a warrant for the arrest of the contemnor.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>cf High Court Rules O 56 r 1(1)</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note></li>
</l>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="Commentary">
<level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.55-2-1" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 55.2.1] Contempt in the face of, or in the hearing of, the court"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.55-2-1" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 55.2.1] </edpnum><title>Contempt in the face of, or in the hearing of, the court</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Misconduct in the courtroom during the proceedings provides the clearest example of contempt in the face, or hearing, of the court. It includes deliberate disruption of the proceedings: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002299" spanref="cr002299-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1970"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="114"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002300" spanref="cr002300-002"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1970"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="1079"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Morris v Crown Office</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002299-001" status="unval">[1970] 2 QB 114</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002300-002">[1970] 1 All ER 1079</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="36973" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (disruption by student protesters); and a deliberate attempt to circumvent a judge&#x2019;s ruling: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002301" spanref="cr002301-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="NSWR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1963"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="1556"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002302" spanref="cr002302-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="SRNSW"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1962"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="190"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Prior; Ex parte Bellanto</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002301-001" status="unval">[1963] NSWR 1556</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002302-002" status="unval">[1962] SR (NSW) 190</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="10635" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Abusive or threatening conduct towards the judge, legal representatives, litigants or other persons in court provides another obvious example of contempt in the face of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002303" spanref="cr002303-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9102677"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">R v Herring</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002303-001"> (NSWSC, Slattery AJ, No 70140/90, 3 October 1991, unreported, BC9102677)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> (prisoner assaulted the judge); <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1985"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002304" spanref="cr002304-001"><ci:reporter value="ACTR"/><ci:volume num="65"/><ci:page num="11"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Director of Public Prosecutions v Jones</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002304-001">(1985) 65 ACTR 11</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="21123" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (defendant in custody threatened with violence). Defiantly disrespectful conduct directed at the judge may also constitute contempt in the face of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002305" spanref="cr002305-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1972"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="317"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Fellows; Ex parte Stewart</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002305-001">[1972] 2 NSWLR 317</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> (opposition to adjournment and insistence on matter being heard); <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002306" spanref="cr002306-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="NSWR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1970"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="23"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Nash; Ex parte Tuckerman</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002306-001" status="unval">[1970] 3 NSWR 23</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="79761" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (defendants gesturing to indicate disregard of court&#x2019;s jurisdiction); cf <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002307" spanref="cr002307-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9101415"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Toner v A-G (NSW)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002307-001"> (NSWCA, Full Court, 19 November 1991, unreported, BC9101415)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> (counsel shouting at judge &#x2014; mere discourtesy not amounting to contempt); <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1995"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002308" spanref="cr002308-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ACrimR"/><ci:volume num="80"/><ci:page num="92"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002309" spanref="cr002309-002"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9503911"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Murphy v Magistrates' Court at Prahran</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002308-001" status="unval">(1995) 80 A Crim R 92</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002309-002"> BC9503911</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="105991" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (complaint of bias not contempt). Similarly, it is a contempt in the face of the court if a witness refuses to leave when ordered to do so: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002310" spanref="cr002310-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1979"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="31"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr002310" spanref="cr002310-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="44" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002311" spanref="cr002311-003"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1978"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="731"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Attorney-General (UK) v Leveller Magazine Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002310-001" status="unval">[1979] QB 31</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr002310-002" status="unval">at 44</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002311-003">[1978] 3 All ER 731</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="241931" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (witness' refusal to leave the court) and see 
<remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.29-5-120" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">[29.5.120]</remotelink>
; or when a competent and compellable witness refuses to be sworn or give evidence: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1991"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002312" spanref="cr002312-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="25"/><ci:page num="1"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Smith v R</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002312-001">(1991) 25 NSWLR 1</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="15884" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1991"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002313" spanref="cr002313-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="25"/><ci:page num="372"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Director of Public Prosecutions v Chidiac</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002313-001">(1991) 25 NSWLR 372</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="35157" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1979"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002314" spanref="cr002314-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="143"/><ci:page num="162"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002315" spanref="cr002315-002"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="25"/><ci:page num="45"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Keeley v Brooking</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002314-001" status="unval">(1979) 143 CLR 162</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002315-002">25 ALR 45</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="14061" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (false assertion of inability to remember); <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1953"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002316" spanref="cr002316-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="90"/><ci:page num="573"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr002316" spanref="cr002316-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="578" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002317" spanref="cr002317-003"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC5301000"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Coward v Stapleton</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002316-001" status="unval">(1953) 90 CLR 573</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr002316-002" status="unval">at 578</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002317-003"> BC5301000</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="13692" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (purported answers). The threat of violence to a legal practitioner in the vicinity of the court constitutes contempt in the face of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1975"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002318" spanref="cr002318-001"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="6"/><ci:page num="307"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Brown v Putnam</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002318-001">(1975) 6 ALR 307</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="59946" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1968"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002319" spanref="cr002319-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="NSWR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1968"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="325"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002320" spanref="cr002320-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNPt"/><ci:volume num="89"/><ci:page num="1"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Goldman</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002319-001" status="unval">[1968] 3 NSWR 325</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002320-002" status="unval">(1968) 89 WN Pt 1 (NSW) 175</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="59945" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Disruption of the proceedings by external noise also constitutes contempt: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002321" spanref="cr002321-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1990"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="397"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Bodden v Cmr of Police</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002321-001" status="unval">[1990] 2 QB 397</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="245141" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Improper restriction of access to the courtroom would also constitute contempt in the face of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1970"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002322" spanref="cr002322-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="NSWR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1970"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="41"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002323" spanref="cr002323-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="SRNSW"/><ci:volume num="72"/><ci:page num="555"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Lucas; Ex parte Tubman</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002322-001" status="unval">[1970] 3 NSWR 41</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002323-002" status="unval">(1970) 72 SR (NSW) 555</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="3179" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. On the other hand, a failure to attend in answer to a properly served subpoena, whilst it constitutes contempt, is not contempt in the face of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1991"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002324" spanref="cr002324-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="25"/><ci:page num="459"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Registrar, Court of Appeal v Maniam (No 1)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002324-001">(1991) 25 NSWLR 459</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="35167" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Between these extremes, there are competing views as to whether, and if so in what circumstances, conduct that does not occur in the actual presence of the presiding judge can be regarded as constituting contempt in the face of the court. In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1986"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002325" spanref="cr002325-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="5"/><ci:page num="445"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">European Asian Bank AG v Wentworth</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002325-001">(1986) 5 NSWLR 445</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1305" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> a scuffle occurred in the courtroom after the judge had adjourned. There the Court of Appeal declined to express a view on the question whether the conduct, which was plainly a contempt of court, should be regarded as having been committed in the face of the court &#x2014; so as to be punishable by the presiding judge under the present rule. In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002326" spanref="cr002326-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1982"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="682"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Registrar, Court of Appeal v Collins</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002326-001">[1982] 1 NSWLR 682</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="2607" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> the alleged contemnors had distributed pamphlets outside the courtroom and it was suggested that this nevertheless could give rise to contempt in the face of the court. Nevertheless, in <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1984"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002327" spanref="cr002327-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1984"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="212"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002328" spanref="cr002328-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ACrimR"/><ci:volume num="15"/><ci:page num="58"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Fraser v R</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002327-001">[1984] 3 NSWLR 212</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002328-002" status="unval">(1984) 15 A Crim R 58</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1304" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> similar conduct was not regarded as contempt in the face of the court.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 55 r 3] r 3 Charge defence and determination">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 55 r 3]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Charge defence and determination</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>3</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Where the contemnor is brought before the Court, the Court shall:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>cause him to be informed orally of the contempt with which he is charged;</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>require him to make his defence to the charge;</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..C"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..C" type="ext"/>(c)</lilabel>
<p><text>after hearing him, determine the matter of the charge; and</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..D"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3..D" type="ext"/>(d)</lilabel>
<p><text>make an order for the punishment or discharge of the contemnor.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>cf HCR O 56 r 1(2)</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note></li>
</l>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R3.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.55-3-1" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 55.3.1] Contemnors right to notice"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.55-3-1" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 55.3.1] </edpnum><title>Contemnors right to notice</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>A person charged with contempt must be given specific notice of the conduct alleged to constitute the contempt and of the action that is liable to be taken against them: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1989"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002329" spanref="cr002329-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="167"/><ci:page num="251"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002330" spanref="cr002330-002"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="86"/><ci:page num="513"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">MacGroarty v A-G (Qld)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002329-001" status="unval">(1989) 167 CLR 251</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002330-002">86 ALR 513</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="15715" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. The person must also be given a reasonable opportunity to prepare: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1984"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr002331" spanref="cr002331-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1984"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="212"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr002332" spanref="cr002332-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ACrimR"/><ci:volume num="15"/><ci:page num="58"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Fraser v R</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002331-001">[1984] 3 NSWLR 212</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr002332-002" status="unval">(1984) 15 A Crim R 58</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1304" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; and present their defence before any order is made: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002333" spanref="cr002333-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1976"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="29"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Skouvakis v Skouvakis</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002333-001">[1976] 2 NSWLR 29</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 55 r 4] r 4 Interim Custody">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 55 r 4]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Interim Custody</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>4</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The Court may, pending disposal of the charge:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1.A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1.A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>direct that the contemnor be kept in such custody as the Court may determine; or</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1.B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1.B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>direct that the contemnor be released.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>cf HCR O 56 r 1(3)</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note></li>
</l>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The Court may make a direction under 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT55.R4.1.B" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">subrule 1(b)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 on terms, which may include a requirement that the contemnor give security, in such sum as the Court directs, for his appearance in person to answer the charge.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>cf HCR O 56 r 1(3)</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level></leg:levelbody></leg:level-vrnt></leg:level></leg:levelbody></leg:level-vrnt></leg:level></leg:body></LEGDOC>